SiteDescription: Monte Soratte is a 690 m high isolated limestone relief 35 km from the centre of Rome
VegDescription: Forest glade bordering a dense evergreen schrubland composed of Pistacia terebinthus, Acer monspessulanum and Fraxinus ornus. The urban area of Sant Oreste is 500 m far.
Publication1: Unpublished data
Publication2: Abbate G., Avena G.C., Blasi C., Veri L., 1981. Studio delle tipologie fitosociologiche del Monte Soratte (Lazio) e loro contributo nella definizione litogeografica dei complessi vegetazionali centro-appenninici. C.N.R., Coli. P.F. "Prom. Qualita dell Ambiente", AQ/1/125, Roma.
Worker1_Address1: Dipartimento di Biologia Ambientale, Universita La Sapienza, Piazzale Aldo Moro, 5, 00185 Roma

SiteDescription: Monte Soratte is a 690 m high isolated limestone relief 35 km from the centre of Rome
VegDescription: Mixed woodland dominated by Quercus ilex, but rich deciduous trees such as Acer monspessulanum, Acer campestre, Fraxinus ornus, Ostrya carpinifolia, and Sorbus torminalis.
Publication1: Unpublished data
Publication2: Abbate G., Avena G.C., Blasi C., Veri L., 1981. Studio delle tipologie fitosociologiche del Monte Soratte (Lazio) e loro contributo nella definizione litogeografica dei complessi vegetazionali centro-appenninici. C.N.R., Coli. P.F. "Prom. Qualita dell Ambiente", AQ/1/125, Roma.
Worker1_Address1: Dipartimento di Biologia Ambientale, Universita La Sapienza, Piazzale Aldo Moro, 5, 00185 Roma

SiteDescription: Monte Soratte is a 690 m high isolated limestone relief 35 km from the centre of Rome
VegDescription: Quercus ilex forest with very few occurrences of Acer monspessulanum and Fraxinus ornus. The understory layer is mostly composed of Cyclamen spp., Smylax aspera and Anemone apennina.
Publication1: Unpublished data
Publication2: Abbate G., Avena G.C., Blasi C., Veri L., 1981. Studio delle tipologie fitosociologiche del Monte Soratte (Lazio) e loro contributo nella definizione litogeografica dei complessi vegetazionali centro-appenninici. C.N.R., Coli. P.F. "Prom. Qualita dell Ambiente", AQ/1/125, Roma.

SiteDescription: Monte Soratte is a 690 m high isolated limestone relief 35 km from the centre of Rome
VegDescription: Forest glade within a semi-open forest, characterized by evergreen and deciduous species, notably Quercus ilex, Phillyrea latifolia, Pistacia terebinthus, Acer monspessulanum and Fraxinus ornus. The urban area of Sant Oreste is 500 m far.

SiteDescription: Monte Soratte is a 690 m high isolated limestone relief 35 km from the centre of Rome
VegDescription: Olive orchards with communities of deciduous Quercus, within arable land planted with Brassica napus and cereals.

SiteDescription: Monte Soratte is a 690 m high isolated limestone relief 35 km from the centre of Rome
VegDescription: Woodland characterized by mixed deciduous oaks mostly represented by Quercus cerris, Carpinus and Rosaceae. The understory is composed of Ruscus aculeatus, Cyclamen spp. and Anemone apennina.

SiteDescription: Coastal area lying on the former Salpi Lagoon in Apulia region
VegDescription: The present landscape of the site is characterized by arable lands mostly cultivated with cereals. This treeless area presents widespread arid pastures rich in Ferula communis, Scolymus hispanicus, Asphodelus spp. and Plantago spp. Sparse olive orchards are present not far from the site. The original lagoonal environment and its brackish vegetation, mostly represented by the genera Salicornia, Sarcocornia, and Salsola of the Amaranthaceae family, are preserved in the close protected wetland of Palude Frattarolo.
Publication1: Di Rita, F., Simone, O., Caldara, M., Gehrels, W.R., Magri, D., 2011. Holocene environmental changes in the coastal Tavoliere Plain (Apulia, southern Italy): a multiproxy approach. Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology, 310, 139–151.

SiteDescription: Tectonic lake close to the easternmost coast of Italian Peninsula
VegDescription: The present vegetation of the area is highly degraded, and the natural evergreen arboreal cover is very limited. The landscape is now characterized by olive groves, cultivated land and stands of planted Pinus halepensis. In the residual patches of maquis the dominant species is Quercus coccifera, mostly accompanied by Olea europaea var. sylvestris, Pistacia lentiscus, Phillyrea latifolia, Arbutus unedo, Erica manipuliflora, Rhamnus alaternus, Myrtus communis, Ceratonia siliqua, and Calycotome spinosa. The shore of Lago Alimini Piccolo is occupied by lush reeds dominated by Phragmites australis. Lago Alimini Grande presents an abundant halophilic flora, with several species of Plantago and Limonium along its shore.
Publication1: Di Rita, F., Magri, D., 2009. Holocene drought, deforestation, and evergreen vegetation development in the central Mediterranean: a 5,500 year record from Lago Alimini Piccolo, Apulia, southeast Italy. The Holocene 19, 295–306

SiteDescription:
The vegetation is characteristic of the oro-Mediterranean thorn cushion plant formations of the High Atlas (Navarro et al. 2009) consisting of sparse shrubs and a range of perennial herbs and grasses. These include cushion-form spiny sub-shrubs such as Bupleurum spinosum Gouan and members of the Fabaceae family (Erinacea anthyllis Link, Cytisus spp., Astragalus spp.), accompanied by low-growing plants from Crassulaceae, Helianthemum spp. and Lamiaceae
(Thymus spp.). Berberis hispanica Boiss. et Reut. and Prunus prostrata Labill. develop in rocky crevices and gullies. There is considerable grazing pressure from sheep and goats. There is little to no tree cover in the
immediate area, excluding occasional junipers (Juniperus thurifera) near the lake itself, and a few trees (Pinus halepensis Mill. and Populus sp.) around the western margin of the lake. Tree cover with J. thurifera and Quercus rotundifolia is developed at
around 20 km distance across the watershed to the northwest on Atlantic (northwest) facing slopes, and Cedrus forest is located around 40 km distance to the northeast on the slopes of Jbel Masker.
VegDescription: Ground cover: 5 Canopy cover: 0, Taxa present: Juniperus phoenicia; Bupleurum spinosum; Apiaceae spp.; Artemisia sp.; Asteraceae spp.; Asteraceae, Carduae; Fabaceae spp.; Poaceae spp.; Scorzonera;
Notes: Hillslope xeric soil on weathered mudstones
Publication1: Bell BA, Fletcher WJ (2016) Modern surface pollen assemblages from the Middle and High Atlas, Morocco: insights into pollen representation and transport. Grana 55:286–301
Worker1_Address1: Geography School of Environment, Education and Development, Arthur Lewis Building, The University of Manchester, Oxford Road, Manchester, M13 9PL, United Kingdom

These include cushion-form spiny sub-shrubs such as Bupleurum spinosum Gouan and members of the Fabaceae family (Erinacea anthyllis Link, Cytisus spp., Astragalus spp.), accompanied by low-growing plants from Crassulaceae, Helianthemum spp. and Lamiaceae
(Thymus spp.). Berberis hispanica Boiss. et Reut. and Prunus prostrata Labill. develop in rocky crevices and gullies. There is considerable grazing pressure from sheep and goats. There is little to no tree cover in the
immediate area, excluding occasional junipers (Juniperus thurifera) near the lake itself, and a few trees (Pinus halepensis Mill. and Populus sp.) around the western margin of the lake. Tree cover with J. thurifera and Quercus rotundifolia is developed at
around 20 km distance across the watershed to the northwest on Atlantic (northwest) facing slopes, and Cedrus forest is located around 40 km distance to the northeast on the slopes of Jbel Masker.
VegDescription: Ground cover: 40 Canopy cover: 0, Taxa present: Alyssum spinosum; Astragalus sp.; Erinacea/Cytisus; Genista sp.; Thymus sp.; Apiaceae spp.; Artemisia sp.; Asteraceae spp.; Asteraceae, Carduae; Euphorbia sp.; Poaceae spp.;
Notes: Xeric soil with loose stone cover
Publication1: Bell BA, Fletcher WJ (2016) Modern surface pollen assemblages from the Middle and High Atlas, Morocco: insights into pollen representation and transport. Grana 55:286–301
Worker1_Address1: Geography School of Environment, Education and Development, Arthur Lewis Building, The University of Manchester, Oxford Road, Manchester, M13 9PL, United Kingdom

SiteDescription:
The site lies within the montane-Mediterranean bioclimate, and the dominant arboreal taxa at the site are Cedrus atlantica, Quercus rotundifolia and Juniperus thurifera. The forest cover around Sidi Ali is degraded by commercial logging, cutting for firewood and grazing pressure. The cedar population at Sidi Ali, which includes individuals of > 900 years in age (Copes-Gerbitz, unpublished dendrochronological data), shows signs of extensive senescence and dieback. Restoration
efforts including planting of seedlings are underway, but there does not yet appear to be widespread establishment of young trees in the area. The surrounding vegetation is a mix of scrub and forest (Morgan 1982; Lecompte 1986). A
wide range of woody taxa can be observed around Sidi Ali, including Ribes uva-crispa L., Rosa spp. and Berberis hispanica along the rocky lake margins, spiny cushion-form shrubs in open areas including Erinacea anthyllis, and a range of mesic tree taxa in the best preserved forest fragments on the north-facing slopes of the lake’s southern margin. These latter include Acer monspessulanum L., Crataegus lacciniata Steven ex Besser and Fraxinus dimorpha Coss. et Dureiu. The lake is a popular tourist spot and the area is subject to extensive animal grazing.
VegDescription: Ground cover: 35 Canopy cover: 0, Taxa present: Crataegus lacciniata; Alyssum spinosum; Artemisia sp.; Asteraceae spp.; Asteraceae, Lactucae; Euphorbia sp.;
Notes: Basalt rocks, ﬁne sands and silts
Publication1: Bell BA, Fletcher WJ (2016) Modern surface pollen assemblages from the Middle and High Atlas, Morocco: insights into pollen representation and transport. Grana 55:286–301
Worker1_Address1: Geography School of Environment, Education and Development, Arthur Lewis Building, The University of Manchester, Oxford Road, Manchester, M13 9PL, United Kingdom

SiteDescription:
The site lies within the montane-Mediterranean bioclimate, and the dominant arboreal taxa at the site are Cedrus atlantica, Quercus rotundifolia and Juniperus thurifera. The forest cover around Sidi Ali is degraded by commercial logging, cutting for firewood and grazing pressure. The cedar population at Sidi Ali, which includes individuals of > 900 years in age (Copes-Gerbitz, unpublished dendrochronological data), shows signs of extensive senescence and dieback. Restoration
efforts including planting of seedlings are underway, but there does not yet appear to be widespread establishment of young trees in the area. The surrounding vegetation is a mix of scrub and forest (Morgan 1982; Lecompte 1986). A
wide range of woody taxa can be observed around Sidi Ali, including Ribes uva-crispa L., Rosa spp. and Berberis hispanica along the rocky lake margins, spiny cushion-form shrubs in open areas including Erinacea anthyllis, and a range of mesic tree taxa in the best preserved forest fragments on the north-facing slopes of the lake’s southern margin. These latter include Acer monspessulanum L., Crataegus lacciniata Steven ex Besser and Fraxinus dimorpha Coss. et Dureiu. The lake is a popular tourist spot and the area is subject to extensive animal grazing.

SiteDescription: Michliffen is a popular touristic destination with a small ski resort, but retains a healthy forest cover (Figure 2G–I), as well as a population of the emblematic Barbary macacques (Macaca sylvanus L.). The southernfacing caldera slopes are covered by a montane Mediterranean mixed needle leaf-broadleaf forest with Cedrus atlantica and Quercus rotundifolia, with other taxa including Acer monspessulanum and Juniperus oxycedrus L. The northern-facing slopes are dominated by stands of C. atlantica.

Notes: Calcareous soil on rocky substrate with organic leaf litter

LocationNotes: Panteleikha River right bedrock bank
VegDescription: Fescue–petrophyte–forb steppe (projective cover 60%; on bare spots, up to 80–90% siltstone fragments). Festuca lenensis Drobow, Poa attenuata Trin., Carex pediformis C.A. Mey, Dracocephalum palmatum Stephan., Thymus diversifolius Klokov, Veron ica incana L., Eremogone tschuktschorum (Regel) Ikonn., Dianthus versicolor Fisch. ex Link., Galium verum L., Pulsatilla multifida (Pritz.) Juz., Potentilla nivea L.

LocationNotes: Panteleikha River right bedrock bank (southern slope, up to 45°), opposite the Ambolikha River inflow
VegDescription:
Grass–petrophyte–forb steppe (projective cover 50%) on a mobile sediment. Plants form pillows or small tussocks retaining the sediment. Dracocephalum palmatum Stephan., Thymus diversifolius Klokov, Eremogone tschuktschorum (Regel) Ikonn., Dianthus versicolor Fisch. ex Link., Festuca lenensis Drobow, Calamagrostis purpurascens R. Br., Pulsatilla multifida (Pritz.) Juz., Potentilla
nivea L.
Publication1: Lopatina & Zanina 2016 Subrecent Spore–Pollen Spectra from the Lower Kolyma River Basin and Their Importance for the Reconstruction of the Quaternary Paleogeography of the Region. Stratigraphy and Geological Correlation, 2016, Vol. 24, No. 2, pp. 203–211

LocationNotes: Panteleikha River right bedrock bank (southern slope, up to 60°), opposite the Ambolikha River inflow
VegDescription: Grass–petrophyte–forb steppe (projective cover up to 60–70%), with bare sediment spots. Plants form tussocks retaining the sediment. Veronica incana L., Dracocephalum palmatum Stephan, Thymus diversifolius Klokov, Festuca lenensis Drobow, Calamagrostis purpurascens R. Br., Artemisia dracunculus L., Potentilla nivea L., Silene stenophylla Ledeb., Allium strictum Schrad., Chamaenerion angustifolium (L.) Scop. The outlier is edged by a larch forest composed of Larix cajanderi Mayr., with undergrowth of Betula divaricata Ledeb., Salix glauca L., Vaccinium vitisidaea L., V. uliginosum L., Rosa acicularis Lindl., and Ledum palustre L.
Publication1: Lopatina & Zanina 2016 Subrecent Spore–Pollen Spectra from the Lower Kolyma River Basin and Their Importance for the Reconstruction of the Quaternary Paleogeography of the Region. Stratigraphy and Geological Correlation, 2016, Vol. 24, No. 2, pp. 203–211
